$frontmatter {
  title: Session
  description: The Session transcript helper — explicit commit model, tool rounds, and branching.
  tags = ["session", "transcript"]
}

"#": Session

"intro" = ```markdown
`Session` is a transcript helper, not a higher-order runtime. It owns a `ModelInput` and an
execution `Lutum`, exposes builder-style turn launchers, and gates all transcript writes behind
explicit `commit_*` calls. It deliberately does not own hidden loops, retries, or branch graphs.
```

"toc".$toc = true

@ "building" {
  "##": Building and Pushing Messages

  "body" = ```markdown
Construct a `Session` from any `Lutum` context:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::{Lutum, Session};

let mut session = Session::new(llm);

// Push messages directly
session.push_system("You are a code review assistant.");
session.push_user("Review this function for readability.");

// Access and modify the underlying ModelInput directly
session.input_mut().push_user("... or build it programmatically");
```

}

@ "commit-model" {
  "##": Explicit Commit Model

  "body" = ```markdown
Running a turn does **not** mutate the transcript. The result exists only in the returned value
until you explicitly commit it:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
// Does NOT change session state
let result = session.text_turn().collect().await?;

// NOW the turn is in the transcript
session.commit_text(result);
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
The same pattern applies to all turn kinds:

| Outcome | Commit method |
|---|---|
| Text turn result | `session.commit_text(result)` |
| Structured turn result | `session.commit_structured(result)` |
| Text turn with tools (finished) | `session.commit_text_with_tools(result)` |
| Structured turn with tools (finished) | `session.commit_structured_with_tools(result)` |
| Tool round | `round.commit(&mut session, tool_results)?` |

This design supports branch evaluation, approval gates, and speculative execution — you can
run a turn, inspect the result, and decide whether to commit or discard.
```

}

@ "tool-rounds" {
  "##": Tool Rounds

  "body" = ```markdown
When the model requests tool calls, the result is a `NeedsTools` variant carrying a `round` object.
`round.commit(...)` validates tool result ordering against the committed turn and atomically records
both the assistant turn and the tool results:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::TextStepOutcomeWithTools;

loop {
    let outcome = session
        .text_turn()
        .tools::<MyTools>()
        .collect()
        .await?;

    match outcome {
        TextStepOutcomeWithTools::NeedsTools(round) => {
            let tool_results = round.tool_calls.iter()
                .cloned()
                .map(|call| execute_tool(call))
                .collect::<Vec<_>>();

            round.commit(&mut session, tool_results)?;
            // loop continues — session now has the assistant + tool results
        }
        TextStepOutcomeWithTools::Finished(result) => {
            println!("{}", result.assistant_text());
            session.commit_text_with_tools(result);
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

  "body-2" = ```markdown
`round.expect_one()?` extracts exactly one tool call and panics if there are zero or more than one.
`round.expect_at_most_one()?` returns `Option<ToolCall>`. Both are convenience helpers for
single-tool scenarios.
```

}

@ "direct-access" {
  "##": Direct Input Access

  "body" = ```markdown
`Session` exposes the underlying `ModelInput` for low-level inspection and mutation:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
// Read-only access
let input: &ModelInput = session.input();

// Mutable access
let input: &mut ModelInput = session.input_mut();

// Take ownership (consumes the session)
let input: ModelInput = session.into_input();
```

}

@ "branching" {
  "##": Branching

  "body" = ```markdown
`Session::clone()` is the branch mechanism. Because nothing is committed until you call
`commit_*`, cloning before a turn gives you two independent transcript histories:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
// Both branches share the same history up to this point
let mut branch_a = session.clone();
let mut branch_b = session.clone();

// Run different turns on each branch
branch_a.push_user("Explain with an analogy.");
branch_b.push_user("Explain with pseudocode.");

let result_a = branch_a.text_turn().collect().await?;
let result_b = branch_b.text_turn().collect().await?;

// Evaluate and pick the better result, then commit it to the original session
let best = pick_better(&result_a, &result_b);
session.commit_text(best);
```

  "note".$mark.alert = "NOTE"
  "note" = ```markdown
The library does not introduce transcript graph semantics or first-class branch structure. If you
need a full branch tree, maintain it in your own data structures using `Session::clone()` as the
primitive.
```

}

@ "defaults" {
  "##": Turn Defaults

  "body" = ```markdown
`SessionDefaults` lets you set temperature, max output tokens, and a system prompt that apply to
every turn launched from the session, without repeating them on each builder call:
```

  "rust-example" = ```rust
use lutum::{Session, SessionDefaults, Temperature};

let defaults = SessionDefaults::default()
    .with_temperature(Temperature::new(0.3)?)
    .with_system("You are a code review assistant.");

let mut session = Session::with_defaults(llm, defaults);
```

}
